    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="A cartoon illustration shows a shadowy figure carrying off a red directory folder, which has a surprised-looking face on its side." src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/MU0jUqxH_k20nll8yPnhnNjf9oo=/0x0:2040x1360/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73659948/VRG_Illo_STK001_B_Sala_Hacker.0.jpg" /&gt;
        &lt;figcaption&gt;Illustration: Beatrice Sala&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="fspbWQ"&gt;The FBI &lt;a href="https://www.justice.gov/usao-dc/pr/fbi-arrests-alabama-man-january-2024-sec-x-hack-spiked-value-bitcoin"&gt;has arrested an Alabama man&lt;/a&gt; who is accused of hacking the Securities and Exchange Commission’s X account in January. The indictment (&lt;a href="https://www.documentcloud.org/documents/25230724-sec-x-hacker-indictment?responsive=1&amp;amp;title=1"&gt;PDF&lt;/a&gt;) alleges that 25-year-old Eric Council Jr. worked with co-conspirators to &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/9/24032095/bitcoin-etf-sec-fake-tweet-x-gary-gensler"&gt;take control of the account&lt;/a&gt; and post a fake message from SEC Chair Gary Gensler about Bitcoin ETFs that caused the price of Bitcoin to jump by more than $1,000 momentarily.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="kudf70"&gt;To carry out this scheme, Council is accused of creating a fake ID using the information belonging to the person in control of the SEC’s X account. He then allegedly tricked AT&amp;amp;T into providing a SIM card with the victim’s phone number and install it into a new iPhone he purchased. Finally, Council was able to gain control of the SEC’s account using...&lt;/p&gt;
